<br>
Heh, funny--that sounds like me. I had a (worthless) BA, and found myself working in retail, trying to support a family. My reasoning was pretty similar to yours: enlist, get some training and experience, get out, find a decent job. So, I became an ET (Electronics Technician), and am working in Satellite Communications. That much went as planned....<br>
<br>
What didn't go as planned was that, after arriving here in (god-awful) Naples, my pregnant wife was immediately sent back stateside, since the hospital here was too low-end to handle a high-risk pregnancy (my wife had high blood pressure). After the baby was born (right after September 11--no one was allowed to take leave, so I missed the birth), we tried and tried to get them over here. A number of other medical issues, some bad luck, and a slew of incompetence (only some of it the Navy's) made it impossible for them to join me. So, nearly three years later, I'm on the verge of going to a new duty station, and will finally be able to live with my wife and son (who barely knows me). Of course, I'll be going to a ship, and will likely be setting out for a good six to nine months pretty soon....<br>
<br>
As for getting out, and finding a job, well.... The telecommunications industry is pretty damned flooded right now (the whole tech sector is, really)--there are hordes of former military Electronics Technicians, as well as Devry and ITT Tech graduates to compete with. Most of the ET friends I know who have gotten out are either struggling stateside, or have taken contract jobs overseas (bleh).<br>
<br>
I'm not trying to scare you out of signing up--my experience has been fairly atypical (though not unique). You just need to be aware of what you're getting into, with open eyes:<br>
<br>
-If you're not sure of what to study in college, absolutely DO NOT GO! You'll waste a LOT of money. The military is a great way to figure things out about yourself, life, and your career. In retrospect, I wish I had joined right after High School, and then gone to college.<br>
<br>
-Military life is murder on families; if you're not single, I really advise against enlisting. My situation aside, I cannot count the number of divorces and separations that have occurred in my work center alone since I got here.<br>
<br>
-Choose your branch of service, and your specialization, very carefully. There's a saying in the Navy: choose your rate, choose your fate. You can learn a lot about military job fields on the internet--do some research before you risk throwing 4+ years of your life away. Had I to it over again, I would have joined the Air Force--the Navy's schools are longer and more comprehensive, but there's a lot to be said for quality of life.<br>
<br>
Whatever you decide, I wish you luck. If you have any questions about the Navy at all, or Navy job fields, feel free to send me an email (makrazhat@yahoo.com), and I'll give you the (relatively) unbiased scoop.<br>
<br>
